{"title_page": "TV Azteca", "text_new": "{{short description|Mexican multimedia conglomerate}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name              = TV Azteca. S.A.B. de C.V.\n| logo              = AZSINCOPY.png \n| caption           = \n| type              = [[S.A. (corporation)|Sociedad An\u00f3nima de Capital Variable]] \n| traded_as         = {{BMV|AZTECACPO|5730}}\n| genre             = \n| fate              = \n| predecessor       = [[Imevisi\u00f3n]] (1983-1993)\n| successor         = \n| foundation        = {{start date and age|mf=yes|1993|08|02}}\n| founder           = [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]]\n| defunct           = \n| location_city     = [[Mexico City]]\n| location_country  = [[Mexico]]\n| location          = \n| locations         = \n| area_served       = \n| key_people        = Benjam\u00edn Salinas Sada <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n| industry          = [[Mass media]]\n| products          = Television broadcasting, radio and multimedia\n| services          = \n| revenue           = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|US$]] 3900million <small>(2012)</small>\n| operating_income  = \n| net_income        = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|US$]] 1850 million <small>(2012)</small>\n| aum               = \n| assets            = \n| equity            = \n| owner             = \n| num_employees     = 6,000\n| parent            = [[Grupo Salinas]]\n| divisions         = \n| subsid            = \n| homepage          = {{URL|http://www.tvazteca.com}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''TV Azteca, S.A.B. de C.V.''' is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] multimedia conglomerate owned by [[Grupo Salinas]]. It is the second-largest [[mass media]] company in [[Mexico]] after [[Televisa]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gruposalinas.com/en/tv-azteca|title=TV Azteca|last=|first=|date=|website=Grupo Salinas|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.perfectsensedigital.com/tv-azteca-deportes-noticias-and-more-sites-replatform-on-brightspot|title=TV Azteca, Mexico\u2019s Second-Largest Mass Media Company, Replatforms on Brightspot|date=2019-08-26|website=Perfect Sense|language=en|access-date=2020-04-18}}</ref> It primarily competes with [[Televisa]] and [[Imagen Televisi\u00f3n]], as well as some local operators. It owns two national television networks, [[Azteca Uno]] and [[Azteca 7]], and operates two other nationally distributed services, [[adn40]] and [[a+ (television channel)|a+]]. All three of these networks have transmitters in most major and minor cities.\n\nTV Azteca also operates ''Azteca Trece Internacional'', reaching 13 countries in [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]], and part of the [[Azteca Am\u00e9rica]] network in the [[United States]]. Its flagship program is the newscast ''[[Hechos]]''.\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\n{{see also|Imevisi\u00f3n}}\n[[Image:TV Azteca logo .svg|thumb|140px|left|TV Azteca logo used between 1993 and 2011]]\nIn the early 1990s, the presidency of [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]] privatized many government assets. Among them was the Instituto Mexicano de la Televisi\u00f3n, known as [[Imevisi\u00f3n]], which owned two national television networks (Red Nacional 7 and Red Nacional 13) and three local TV stations. In preparation for the privatization, the Imevisi\u00f3n stations were parceled into a variety of newly created companies, the largest of which was named Televisi\u00f3n Azteca, S.A. de C.V.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Peschard-Sverdrup|first=Armand B.|url=https://books.google.com.br/books?id=mvTdHGuBiBYC&pg=PA281&lpg=PA281&dq=tv+azteca+imevision&source=bl&ots=B6ItIU9T6v&sig=ACfU3U1dvmrxwxwnP4HOHPSTi8E9tUnX7w&hl=pt-BR&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwiBubO1lvHoAhUMErkGHdk1AO4Q6AEwB3oECAsQLA#v=onepage&q=tv%20azteca%20imevision&f=false|title=Mexican Governance: From Single-party Rule to Divided Government|last2=Rioff|first2=Sara|date=2005|publisher=CSIS|year=|isbn=978-0-89206-457-1|location=|pages=281|language=en}}</ref>\n\nWith the exception of [[XEIMT-TDT|Canal 22]], which was spun off to [[Conaculta]], one bidder won all of the stations. On July 18, 1993,<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Political and mobile media landscape in M\u00e9xico: the case of #yosoy132|last = Goggin; Albarr\u00e1n|first = G.;C.|date = 2014|journal = Continuum: Journal of Media & Cultural Studies|doi = |pmid = |access-date = }}</ref> Mexico's Finance Ministry, the [[Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit|''Secretar\u00eda de Hacienda y Cr\u00e9dito P\u00fablico'']] (SHCP), announced that Radio Televisora del Centro, a group controlled by [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]], was the winner of the auction to acquire the \"state-owned media package\", which also included Imevisi\u00f3n's studios in the [[Ajusco]] area of Mexico City. The winning bid amounted to US$645 million. The new group soon took on the Televisi\u00f3n Azteca name for the entire operation and soon challenged Televisa, turning what had been a television monopoly into a television duopoly. The two conglomerates held 97 percent of the commercial television concessions in the country.<ref name=\":0\">Mahan, E. (1985). Mexican Broadcasting: Reassessing the Industry-State Relationship. Journal of Communication, 35(1), 60-75.</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\n[[File:TV-Azteca,_M\u00e9rida,_Yucat\u00e1n_(01).jpg|thumb|right|250px|TV-Azteca, M\u00e9rida, Yucat\u00e1n.]]\nIn 1998, TV Azteca announced an investment of US$25 million in [[XHTVM-TDT|XHTVM-TV]], which was owned by Javier Moreno Valle through concessionaire Televisora del Valle de M\u00e9xico, S.A. de C.V. Under the deal, Azteca restructured TVM and took control of ad sales and most programming duties, while Moreno Valle's CNI news service retained some primetime space. However, in 2000, Moreno Valle broke the contract with Azteca, alleging Azteca of filling up time allotted to CNI and not fulfilling the obligations in the contract. In December 2002, Azteca used private security guards to retake control of the XHTVM facilities on Cerro del Chiquihuite in Mexico City. However, the Mexican government stepped into the dispute and forced Azteca to relinquish control of XHTVM. In 2005, an employee strike that crippled CNI, Moreno Valle's mounting legal troubles, and a deal with the 5% owner of the concessionaire allowed Azteca to buy the remainder of the station and retake control of XHTVM, under the name Proyecto 40, in 2006.\n\nOn March 7, 2011, TV Azteca changed its name to ''Azteca'', reflecting its growth into a multimedia company.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tvazteca.com/capitulos/vengalaalegria/39479/azteca-se-renueva-para-ti |title= Azteca se renueva para ti (\"Azteca renews for you\") |author= TV Azteca |date= March 7, 2011 |language= spanish |accessdate= March 14, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717114705/http://www.tvazteca.com/capitulos/vengalaalegria/39479/azteca-se-renueva-para-ti |archivedate= July 17, 2011 }}</ref> However, in July 2015, the TV Azteca name was restored.\n\nTV Azteca is the second largest mass media company in M\u00e9xico after Televisa.<ref name=\":0\"/> These two big organizations control the 97% of mass media in Mexico.<ref name=\":0\" /> TV Azteca was funded in 1993 by Ricardo Salinas Pliego. TV Azteca has 31% of the 465 television concessions in M\u00e9xico.<ref name=\":0\" /> The auction of the state channels and the granting of further concessions to TV Azteca further strengthen their connection. It also owns Azteca banks, Azteca insurance, Iusacell, programing pay television, cinemas, live theater, news channels, newspapers, Azteca music, an acting school, Azteca consumer products, Azteca internet, Azteca series, Azteca sports, stadiums, etc. TV Azteca is another company which also serves the government however to a much lesser extent than Televisa.<ref>Murphy, P. D. (1995, December). Television and cultural politics in M\u00e9xico: Some notes on Televisa, the state and transnational culture. The Howard journal of communication, pp. pp. 250-</ref> TV Azteca also receives lucrative contracts from the Mexican government, and therefore the information that emits is also controlled by the actual government.  The news that is normally emitted by TV Azteca is 25% news bulletins that come from advertising, and infotainment relying on celebrities and biased editorials.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Services==\n\n===Terrestrial networks===\nIn Mexico:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Network'''\n| '''[[Flagship (broadcasting)|Flagship]]'''\n| '''[[Broadcast programming|Programming]]'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca Uno|Azteca 1]]''' \n| [[XHDF-TDT|XHDF 1]]\n| general programming and news and first-run [[telenovelas]]\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca 7]]'''\n| [[XHIMT-TDT|XHIMT 7]]\n| general programming, sports, and series\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[XHTVM-TDT|adn40]]'''\n| [[XHTVM-TDT|XHTVM 26]]\n| news and informational shows\n|}\n\nOutside Mexico:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Network'''\n| '''[[Flagship (broadcasting)|Flagship]]'''\n| '''[[Broadcast programming|Programming]]'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca Guatemala]]''' \n| N/A\n| [[Guatemala]]n channel with programming from TV Azteca's three television national networks in Mexico and local news\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca Honduras]]'''\n| N/A\n| [[Honduras|Honduran]] channel with programming from TV Azteca's three television national networks in Mexico and local news\n|}\n\n===Formerly Owned===\n*[[Azteca Am\u00e9rica]]: [[United States|U.S.]] channel with programming from TV Azteca's three television national networks in Mexico and local news\n*[[KAZA-TV]] used to be the flagship of Azteca America from 2001-2018 but was sold to [[Chicago]]-based [[Weigel Broadcasting]], which stripped KAZA of its flagship status, and was replaced by MeTV as an O&O.\n\n===Cable===\n* '''Az Noticias'''\n* '''Az Clic!'''\n* '''Az Mundo'''\n* '''Az Coraz\u00f3n'''\n* '''Az Cinema'''\n* '''Azteca Trece -1 hora'''\n* '''Azteca Trece -2 horas'''\n* '''Romanza+ \u00c1frica''' - African channel\n\n==Disputes and controversies==\n{{main|Ricardo Salinas Pliego}}\nOn 5 January 2005, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) accused TV Azteca executives (including chairman [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]]) of having personally profited from a multimillion-dollar debt fraud committed by TV Azteca and another company in which they held stock.<ref name=\"NYT\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/05/business/media/05azteca.html The New York Times > Business > Media & Advertising > Chairman of TV Azteca Is Charged With Fraud] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522153757/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/05/business/media/05azteca.html |date=2013-05-22 }}, Patrick McGeehan, ''New York Times'', January 5, 2005.</ref> The charges were among the first brought under the provisions of the [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act]] of 2002,<ref name=NYT/> introduced in the wake of the [[Accounting scandals|corporate financial scandals]] of that year.\n\n{{main|Ley Televisa}}\nThe [[Ley Televisa|Federal Radio and Television Law]] (known as the Ley Televisa) was a bill concerning the licensing and regulation of the electromagnetic spectrum. The LFRT was favorable to both TV Azteca and Televisa (who together control 95 percent of all television frequencies) because it allowed them to renew their licenses without paying for them. According to ''[[The Economist]]'', the Ley Federal de Radio y Televisi\u00f3n \"raced through Congress confirming the country's longstanding television duopoly\" and constituted a \"giveaway of radio spectrum and a provision that allows broadcasting licenses to be renewed more or less automatically\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/node/9257810|title=Court TV|date=2007-05-31|journal=The Economist|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212160355/http://www.economist.com/node/9257810|archivedate=2018-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, TV Azteca networks ([[XHIMT-TV|Azteca 7]], [[XHDF-TV|Azteca 13]], and [[XHTVM-TV|Proyecto 40]]) were dropped by Mexican cable-TV carriers representing more than 4 million subscribers in a [[carriage dispute]] over terms. Cable operators claimed that Azteca wanted to charge a fee by packaging its over-the-air stations with cable networks, such as news and soap opera channels, which potentially represented a higher cost to subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-02-14/tv-azteca-dropped-by-mexico-cable-carriers-over-pricing-dispute|title=TV Azteca Loses 4 Million Cable Viewers in Price Dispute|date=14 February 2012|via=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808160746/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-02-14/tv-azteca-dropped-by-mexico-cable-carriers-over-pricing-dispute|archivedate=8 August 2016}}</ref> After a nine-month absence, TV Azteca returned gradually to cable operators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anmtvla.com/2013/02/mexico-tv-azteca-regresa-cable.html|title=Mexico: TV Azteca regresa a Cable - Anime, Manga y TV|website=www.anmtvla.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307022407/http://www.anmtvla.com/2013/02/mexico-tv-azteca-regresa-cable.html|archivedate=2013-03-07}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[American Tower]]'s Mexican Unit, MATC Infraestructura sued TV Azteca for $97 Million in a New York court for defaulting on a loan from the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-azteca-idUSKBN1KU2OJ|title=American Tower feud 'not positive' for Mexico's TV Azteca, Fitch says|date=9 August 2018|via=www.reuters.com|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Holdings ==\nTV Azteca is part of the conglomerate [[Grupo Salinas]], which includes the [[Grupo Elektra]] franchise of department stores, the [[Banco Azteca]] bank, and [[Seguros Azteca]] life insurance. TV Azteca also owns [[Liga MX]] soccer club, [[Monarcas Morelia]].\n\n===Acting school===\nThe network has set up an acting school, Centro de Estudios y Formaci\u00f3n Actoral (CEFAC). Alumni include [[Iliana Fox]], [[Luis Ernesto Franco]], [[Adriana Louvier]], [[Fran Meric]], [[B\u00e1rbara Mori]], [[Laura Palma]] and [[Adri\u00e1n Rubio]].\n\n===Record label===\nThe network also owns a record label, Azteca Music,<ref>Billboard - 25 Oct 1997 - Page 54 \"The theme song of TV Azteca's new telenovela \"Demasiado Corazon\" was written and performed by noted salsero Willie Colon, who is signed in Mexico to Azteca's record label Azteca Music.\"</ref> which was founded in 1996.<ref>Florence Toussaint Alcaraz, ''TV sin fronteras'' - 1998 - Page 136: \"Tambi\u00e9n en 1996, Televisi\u00f3n Azteca inici\u00f3 su incursi\u00f3n en el negocio de los discos. Azteca Music se llama la nueva compa\u00f1\u00eda, que como primer t\u00edtulo de su cat\u00e1logo tiene Nada personal, tema de la telenovela del mismo nombre compuesto ...</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Televisa]]\n* [[List of Broadcasting Companies in Latin America]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|TV Azteca}}\n* [http://www.tvazteca.com/ Azteca official website]\n\n{{IPC companies}}\n{{Mexico Broadcast Television}}\n{{Grupo Salinas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azteca (Multimedia Conglomerate)}}\n[[Category:TV Azteca| ]]\n[[Category:Television broadcasting companies of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Grupo Salinas]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bolsa Mexicana de Valores]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Mexican multimedia conglomerate}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name              = TV Azteca. S.A.B. de C.V.\n| logo              = AZSINCOPY.png \n| caption           = \n| type              = [[S.A. (corporation)|Sociedad An\u00f3nima de Capital Variable]] \n| traded_as         = {{BMV|AZTECACPO|5730}}\n| genre             = \n| fate              = \n| predecessor       = [[Imevisi\u00f3n]] (1983-1993)\n| successor         = \n| foundation        = {{start date and age|mf=yes|1993|08|02}}\n| founder           = [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]]\n| defunct           = \n| location_city     = [[Mexico City]]\n| location_country  = [[Mexico]]\n| location          = \n| locations         = \n| area_served       = \n| key_people        = Benjam\u00edn Salinas Sada <small>([[CEO]])</small>\n| industry          = [[Mass media]]\n| products          = Television broadcasting, radio and multimedia\n| services          = \n| revenue           = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|US$]] 3900million <small>(2012)</small>\n| operating_income  = \n| net_income        = {{profit}} [[United States dollar|US$]] 1850 million <small>(2012)</small>\n| aum               = \n| assets            = \n| equity            = \n| owner             = \n| num_employees     = 6,000\n| parent            = [[Grupo Salinas]]\n| divisions         = \n| subsid            = \n| homepage          = {{URL|http://www.tvazteca.com}}\n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''TV Azteca, S.A.B. de C.V.''' is a [[Mexico|Mexican]] multimedia conglomerate owned by [[Grupo Salinas]]. It is the second-largest [[mass media]] company in [[Mexico]] after [[Televisa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://latercera.com/noticia/negocios/2011/04/655-358540-9-televisa-bajo-41-sus-ganancias-en-el-primer-trimestre-de-2011.shtml |title=Televisa baja sus ganancias en primer trimestre de 2011 |publisher=Diario LaTercera (Chile) |date=2011-04-15 |accessdate=2011-11-05 |url-status=live |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20110927015631/http://latercera.com/noticia/negocios/2011/04/655-358540-9-televisa-bajo-41-sus-ganancias-en-el-primer-trimestre-de-2011.shtml |archivedate=2011-09-27 }}</ref><ref>[http://www.maned.com/news/pressreleases/120309]{{dead link|date=October 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> It primarily competes with [[Televisa]] and [[Imagen Televisi\u00f3n]], as well as some local operators. It owns two national television networks, [[Azteca Uno]] and [[Azteca 7]], and operates two other nationally distributed services, [[adn40]] and [[a+ (television channel)|a+]]. All three of these networks have transmitters in most major and minor cities.\n\nTV Azteca also operates ''Azteca Trece Internacional'', reaching 13 countries in [[Central America|Central]] and [[South America]], and part of the [[Azteca Am\u00e9rica]] network in the [[United States]]. Its flagship program is the newscast ''[[Hechos]]''.\n\n==History==\n===Formation===\n{{see also|Imevisi\u00f3n}}\n[[Image:TV Azteca logo .svg|thumb|140px|left|TV Azteca logo used between 1993 and 2011]]\nIn the early 1990s, the presidency of [[Carlos Salinas de Gortari]] privatized many government assets. Among them was the Instituto Mexicano de la Televisi\u00f3n, known as [[Imevisi\u00f3n]], which owned two national television networks (Red Nacional 7 and Red Nacional 13) and three local TV stations. In preparation for the privatization, the Imevisi\u00f3n stations were parceled into a variety of newly created companies, the largest of which was named Televisi\u00f3n Azteca, S.A. de C.V.\n\nWith the exception of [[XEIMT-TDT|Canal 22]], which was spun off to [[Conaculta]], one bidder won all of the stations. On July 18, 1993,<ref>{{Cite journal|url = |title = Political and mobile media landscape in M\u00e9xico: the case of #yosoy132|last = Goggin; Albarr\u00e1n|first = G.;C.|date = 2014|journal = Continuum: Journal of Media & Cultural Studies|doi = |pmid = |access-date = }}</ref> Mexico's Finance Ministry, the [[Secretariat of Finance and Public Credit|''Secretar\u00eda de Hacienda y Cr\u00e9dito P\u00fablico'']] (SHCP), announced that Radio Televisora del Centro, a group controlled by [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]], was the winner of the auction to acquire the \"state-owned media package\", which also included Imevisi\u00f3n's studios in the [[Ajusco]] area of Mexico City. The winning bid amounted to US$645 million. The new group soon took on the Televisi\u00f3n Azteca name for the entire operation and soon challenged Televisa, turning what had been a television monopoly into a television duopoly. The two conglomerates held 97 percent of the commercial television concessions in the country.<ref name=\":0\">Mahan, E. (1985). Mexican Broadcasting: Reassessing the Industry-State Relationship. Journal of Communication, 35(1), 60-75.</ref>\n\n===Expansion===\n[[File:TV-Azteca,_M\u00e9rida,_Yucat\u00e1n_(01).jpg|thumb|right|250px|TV-Azteca, M\u00e9rida, Yucat\u00e1n.]]\nIn 1998, TV Azteca announced an investment of US$25 million in [[XHTVM-TDT|XHTVM-TV]], which was owned by Javier Moreno Valle through concessionaire Televisora del Valle de M\u00e9xico, S.A. de C.V. Under the deal, Azteca restructured TVM and took control of ad sales and most programming duties, while Moreno Valle's CNI news service retained some primetime space. However, in 2000, Moreno Valle broke the contract with Azteca, alleging Azteca of filling up time allotted to CNI and not fulfilling the obligations in the contract. In December 2002, Azteca used private security guards to retake control of the XHTVM facilities on Cerro del Chiquihuite in Mexico City. However, the Mexican government stepped into the dispute and forced Azteca to relinquish control of XHTVM. In 2005, an employee strike that crippled CNI, Moreno Valle's mounting legal troubles, and a deal with the 5% owner of the concessionaire allowed Azteca to buy the remainder of the station and retake control of XHTVM, under the name Proyecto 40, in 2006.\n\nOn March 7, 2011, TV Azteca changed its name to ''Azteca'', reflecting its growth into a multimedia company.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.tvazteca.com/capitulos/vengalaalegria/39479/azteca-se-renueva-para-ti |title= Azteca se renueva para ti (\"Azteca renews for you\") |author= TV Azteca |date= March 7, 2011 |language= spanish |accessdate= March 14, 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717114705/http://www.tvazteca.com/capitulos/vengalaalegria/39479/azteca-se-renueva-para-ti |archivedate= July 17, 2011 }}</ref> However, in July 2015, the TV Azteca name was restored.\n\nTV Azteca is the second largest mass media company in M\u00e9xico after Televisa.<ref name=\":0\"/> These two big organizations control the 97% of mass media in Mexico.<ref name=\":0\" /> TV Azteca was funded in 1993 by Ricardo Salinas Pliego. TV Azteca has 31% of the 465 television concessions in M\u00e9xico.<ref name=\":0\" /> The auction of the state channels and the granting of further concessions to TV Azteca further strengthen their connection. It also owns Azteca banks, Azteca insurance, Iusacell, programing pay television, cinemas, live theater, news channels, newspapers, Azteca music, an acting school, Azteca consumer products, Azteca internet, Azteca series, Azteca sports, stadiums, etc. TV Azteca is another company which also serves the government however to a much lesser extent than Televisa.<ref>Murphy, P. D. (1995, December). Television and cultural politics in M\u00e9xico: Some notes on Televisa, the state and transnational culture. The Howard journal of communication, pp. pp. 250-</ref> TV Azteca also receives lucrative contracts from the Mexican government, and therefore the information that emits is also controlled by the actual government.  The news that is normally emitted by TV Azteca is 25% news bulletins that come from advertising, and infotainment relying on celebrities and biased editorials.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Services==\n\n===Terrestrial networks===\nIn Mexico:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Network'''\n| '''[[Flagship (broadcasting)|Flagship]]'''\n| '''[[Broadcast programming|Programming]]'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca Uno|Azteca 1]]''' \n| [[XHDF-TDT|XHDF 1]]\n| general programming and news and first-run [[telenovelas]]\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca 7]]'''\n| [[XHIMT-TDT|XHIMT 7]]\n| general programming, sports, and series\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[XHTVM-TDT|adn40]]'''\n| [[XHTVM-TDT|XHTVM 26]]\n| news and informational shows\n|}\n\nOutside Mexico:\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| '''Network'''\n| '''[[Flagship (broadcasting)|Flagship]]'''\n| '''[[Broadcast programming|Programming]]'''\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca Guatemala]]''' \n| N/A\n| [[Guatemala]]n channel with programming from TV Azteca's three television national networks in Mexico and local news\n|- style=\"vertical-align: top; text-align: left;\"\n| '''[[Azteca Honduras]]'''\n| N/A\n| [[Honduras|Honduran]] channel with programming from TV Azteca's three television national networks in Mexico and local news\n|}\n\n===Formerly Owned===\n*[[Azteca Am\u00e9rica]]: [[United States|U.S.]] channel with programming from TV Azteca's three television national networks in Mexico and local news\n*[[KAZA-TV]] used to be the flagship of Azteca America from 2001-2018 but was sold to [[Chicago]]-based [[Weigel Broadcasting]], which stripped KAZA of its flagship status, and was replaced by MeTV as an O&O.\n\n===Cable===\n* '''Az Noticias'''\n* '''Az Clic!'''\n* '''Az Mundo'''\n* '''Az Coraz\u00f3n'''\n* '''Az Cinema'''\n* '''Azteca Trece -1 hora'''\n* '''Azteca Trece -2 horas'''\n* '''Romanza+ \u00c1frica''' - African channel\n\n==Disputes and controversies==\n{{main|Ricardo Salinas Pliego}}\nOn 5 January 2005, the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) accused TV Azteca executives (including chairman [[Ricardo Salinas Pliego]]) of having personally profited from a multimillion-dollar debt fraud committed by TV Azteca and another company in which they held stock.<ref name=\"NYT\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/05/business/media/05azteca.html The New York Times > Business > Media & Advertising > Chairman of TV Azteca Is Charged With Fraud] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130522153757/http://www.nytimes.com/2005/01/05/business/media/05azteca.html |date=2013-05-22 }}, Patrick McGeehan, ''New York Times'', January 5, 2005.</ref> The charges were among the first brought under the provisions of the [[Sarbanes-Oxley Act]] of 2002,<ref name=NYT/> introduced in the wake of the [[Accounting scandals|corporate financial scandals]] of that year.\n\n{{main|Ley Televisa}}\nThe [[Ley Televisa|Federal Radio and Television Law]] (known as the Ley Televisa) was a bill concerning the licensing and regulation of the electromagnetic spectrum. The LFRT was favorable to both TV Azteca and Televisa (who together control 95 percent of all television frequencies) because it allowed them to renew their licenses without paying for them. According to ''[[The Economist]]'', the Ley Federal de Radio y Televisi\u00f3n \"raced through Congress confirming the country's longstanding television duopoly\" and constituted a \"giveaway of radio spectrum and a provision that allows broadcasting licenses to be renewed more or less automatically\".<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.economist.com/node/9257810|title=Court TV|date=2007-05-31|journal=The Economist|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212160355/http://www.economist.com/node/9257810|archivedate=2018-02-12}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2012, TV Azteca networks ([[XHIMT-TV|Azteca 7]], [[XHDF-TV|Azteca 13]], and [[XHTVM-TV|Proyecto 40]]) were dropped by Mexican cable-TV carriers representing more than 4 million subscribers in a [[carriage dispute]] over terms. Cable operators claimed that Azteca wanted to charge a fee by packaging its over-the-air stations with cable networks, such as news and soap opera channels, which potentially represented a higher cost to subscribers.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-02-14/tv-azteca-dropped-by-mexico-cable-carriers-over-pricing-dispute|title=TV Azteca Loses 4 Million Cable Viewers in Price Dispute|date=14 February 2012|via=www.bloomberg.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808160746/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2012-02-14/tv-azteca-dropped-by-mexico-cable-carriers-over-pricing-dispute|archivedate=8 August 2016}}</ref> After a nine-month absence, TV Azteca returned gradually to cable operators.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anmtvla.com/2013/02/mexico-tv-azteca-regresa-cable.html|title=Mexico: TV Azteca regresa a Cable - Anime, Manga y TV|website=www.anmtvla.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130307022407/http://www.anmtvla.com/2013/02/mexico-tv-azteca-regresa-cable.html|archivedate=2013-03-07}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2018, [[American Tower]]'s Mexican Unit, MATC Infraestructura sued TV Azteca for $97 Million in a New York court for defaulting on a loan from the company.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-mexico-azteca-idUSKBN1KU2OJ|title=American Tower feud 'not positive' for Mexico's TV Azteca, Fitch says|date=9 August 2018|via=www.reuters.com|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n== Holdings ==\nTV Azteca is part of the conglomerate [[Grupo Salinas]], which includes the [[Grupo Elektra]] franchise of department stores, the [[Banco Azteca]] bank, and [[Seguros Azteca]] life insurance. TV Azteca also owns [[Liga MX]] soccer club, [[Monarcas Morelia]].\n\n===Acting school===\nThe network has set up an acting school, Centro de Estudios y Formaci\u00f3n Actoral (CEFAC). Alumni include [[Iliana Fox]], [[Luis Ernesto Franco]], [[Adriana Louvier]], [[Fran Meric]], [[B\u00e1rbara Mori]], [[Laura Palma]] and [[Adri\u00e1n Rubio]].\n\n===Record label===\nThe network also owns a record label, Azteca Music,<ref>Billboard - 25 Oct 1997 - Page 54 \"The theme song of TV Azteca's new telenovela \"Demasiado Corazon\" was written and performed by noted salsero Willie Colon, who is signed in Mexico to Azteca's record label Azteca Music.\"</ref> which was founded in 1996.<ref>Florence Toussaint Alcaraz, ''TV sin fronteras'' - 1998 - Page 136: \"Tambi\u00e9n en 1996, Televisi\u00f3n Azteca inici\u00f3 su incursi\u00f3n en el negocio de los discos. Azteca Music se llama la nueva compa\u00f1\u00eda, que como primer t\u00edtulo de su cat\u00e1logo tiene Nada personal, tema de la telenovela del mismo nombre compuesto ...</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Televisa]]\n* [[List of Broadcasting Companies in Latin America]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons cat|TV Azteca}}\n* [http://www.tvazteca.com/ Azteca official website]\n\n{{IPC companies}}\n{{Mexico Broadcast Television}}\n{{Grupo Salinas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Azteca (Multimedia Conglomerate)}}\n[[Category:TV Azteca| ]]\n[[Category:Television broadcasting companies of Mexico]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mexico City]]\n[[Category:Grupo Salinas]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:Media companies established in 1993]]\n[[Category:1993 establishments in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Bolsa Mexicana de Valores]]\n", "name_user": "A.WagnerC", "label": "safe", "comment": "refs. I removed dead refs", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/TV_Azteca"}
{"title_page": "Bladee", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Bladee\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = File:Bladee in Toronto, Canada 2016.jpg\n| caption          = Bladee performing in 2016\n| birth_name       = Benjamin Reichwald\n| alias            = Ken Burns (Sm\u00f6g Boys)\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1994|4|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Stockholm, Sweden]]\n| genre            = [[cloud rap]], [[emo rap]], [[experimental pop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[Singing|singer]], [[Fashion designer]], [[Graphic designer]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Digital Audio Workstation]], [[pitch-correction software]]\n| years_active     = 2008; 2011; 2012\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[YEAR0001]]|[[AWAL]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Yung Lean]]|[[Thaiboy Digital]]|[[ECCO2K]]|Whitearmor|Yung Sherman|Gud|Adamn Killa|Cartier'GOD|Black Kray}}\n}}\n'''Benjamin Thage Dag Reichwald'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/artists/Bladee|title=Bladee|last=|first=|date=|website=Genius|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Borelli-Persson |first1=Laird |title=Is There Anything He Can't Do? Meet Stockholm's Stylish Multi-Hyphenate Zak Arogundade |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/musicians-zak-arogundade |website=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> (born 9 April 1994<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BladeeCity |number=718871748674850816 |date=9 Apr 2016 |title=Thanks everyone that wished me happy birthday}}</ref>), known professionally as '''Bladee''' (pronounced either \"blade\" or \"blade-e\"),<ref>\"Nardwuar vs. Yung Lean\", Youtube video, 12:36, posted by \"[[Nardwuar the Human Serviette|NardwuarServiette]]\", July 23, 2014, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=723ywF5faV4.</ref> is a Swedish rapper, singer, songwriter, record-producer, fashion designer and member of the musical group [[Drain Gang]].<ref name=Darville2018>{{cite web |last1=Darville |first1=Jordan |title=Listen to Bladee's new album Red Light |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/05/11/bladee-album-red-light-stream |website=[[The Fader]] |publisher=Andy Cohn |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Red Light album review\">\"Bladee - Red Light ALBUM REVIEW\", Youtube video, 5:21, posted by \"[[Anthony Fantano|theneedledrop]]\", June 21, 2018, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FJwmTnjDkrI.</ref><ref name=\"debut Decay\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Steffanee |title=Bladee debuts \"Decay,\" our first taste of new album Red Light |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/05/02/bladee-decay-video-red-light-album |website=[[The Fader]] |publisher=Andy Cohn |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nHe released his debut album ''[[Eversince (Bladee album)|Eversince]]'' in 2016, and his second album ''[[Red Light (Bladee album)|Red Light]]'' in 2018\u2014both through Stockholm record label [[YEAR0001]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jenkins |first1=Craig |title=Stream Yung Lean Associate Bladee's Chilly, Gorgeous Debut Album 'Eversince' |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/6e43we/stream-yung-lean-associate-yung-bladees-chilly-gorgeous-debut-album-eversince |website=[[Noisey]] |publisher=[[Vice Media]] |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=Darville2018 /><ref>YEAR0001. Accessed July 19, 2018. http://www.year0001.com/.</ref> In addition to his music, Reichwald creates visual art, which frequently appears as cover art for his releases.<ref>Sami Baha. \"Bladee - Cover Up (Prod. Sami Baha)\". Soundcloud audio, 2:38, June 27, 2018. https://soundcloud.com/samibaha/bladee-cover-up-prod-sami-baha.</ref><ref>Bala Club. \"Woesum - Sapphire\". Soundcloud audio, 5:05, December 23, 2017. https://soundcloud.com/balaclub/woesum-sapphire.</ref> Reichwald also serves as the creative director for [[Yung Lean|Yung Lean's]] clothing line Sadboys Gear.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tesema |first1=Feleg |title=5 of Our Favorite New Collections & Where to Buy Them |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/new-clothing-collections/ |website=[[Highsnobiety]] |publisher=Titel Media |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"need to know\">{{cite web |last1=Dunn |first1=Frankie |title=10 things you need to know about bladee |url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/xwmzgz/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-bladee |website=[[i-D]] |publisher=[[Vice Media|Vice]] |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBenjamin Reichwald was born 9 April 1994 in Stockholm, Sweden<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BladeeCity/status/718871748674850816|title=Thanks everyone that wish me happy birthday|last=BLAD\u018eE|date=2016-04-09|website=@BladeeCity|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> and was raised mainly in the [[Skanstull]] area.<ref name=BeingBlade>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/09/17/bladee-interview-drain-gang-trash-island|title=Being Bladee|last=|first=|date=17 September 2019|website=The Fader|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was here where, in 2004, he met fellow Gravity Boys member Zak Arogundade, also known as Ecco2k. The two were classmates and formed a band titled \"Krossad\" when Reichwald was 13, which led to Reichwald's interest in music.<ref name=BeingBlade /> \n\nAfter leaving school, Reichwald began to get into making music whilst working at a daycare centre.<ref name=\"punk mix\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aqnb.com/2014/07/09/bladee-old-swedish-hardcore-punk-mix/|title=Bladee, old swedish hardcore punk mix|date=2014-07-09|website=atractivoquenobello|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nReichwald released a few tracks in 2011 under the name Ken Burns<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Bladee-tony-hawk-lyrics|title=Tony Hawk|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ipMrg0edjBM|title=Tony Hawk|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, but properly began releasing music in 2012. He eventually became friends with fellow Swedish rapper [[Yung Lean]], who was a friend of Reichwald's brother. Reichwald eventually sent a message to Sad Boys member Yung Sherman on SoundCloud, asking to collaborate, which resulted in a working relationship between his own Gravity Boys collective and Lean's Sad Boys Entertainment. Reichwald and Lean then made \"Heal You // Bladerunner\" from Lean's Unknown Death 2002 mixtape, which gave him attention from Lean's fanbase.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2014/07/16/taking-arizona-iced-tea-and-making-it-cry-an-interview-with-yung-lean-and-the-sad-boys|title=\"Taking Arizona Iced Tea and Making It Cry\": An Interview with Yung Lean and the Sad Boys|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nReichwald released his debut-mixtape, ''GLUEE'' in 2014 on the YEAR0001 label<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://year0001.com/label/cases/yr0005|title=Bladee - Gluee {{!}} YEAR0001|website=year0001.com|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> which was described as the \"summertime anthem for a suburban generation stuck scrolling through Twitter\".<ref name=\"punk mix\"\" /> The mixtape was successful on the audio distribution platform SoundCloud, racking up over 2 million plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0nC0I-z9ONs|title=Always High|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This mixtape, coupled with several singles going viral and features on Yung Leans debut mixtape [[Unknown Death 2002]] was able to rocket Bladee into underground hip hop fame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/thoughtsofamusicwriter/chronicling-how-sad-boys-and-shield-gang-became-swedens-top-rap-groups-c90925789e6c|title=Chronicling How Sad Boys and Shield Gang Became Sweden's Top Rap Groups|last=Osman|first=Jibril|date=2017-12-20|website=Medium|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nReichwald released his debut album, ''[[Eversince]]'' on May 25th, 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/05/25/bladee-eversince-album-stream||title=Hear Swedish Sing-Rapper Bladee\u2019s Debut Album Eversince|date=May 25, 2016|author=Cooper, Duncan|work=[[The Fader]]|access-date=September 10, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> The album received mixed reviews from mainstream outlets, but was well-received by underground and experimental critics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gaffa.se/recension/107456/kliver-ur-yung-leans-skugga-med-briljant-debut/||title=Kliver ur Yung Leans skugga med briljant debut|date=June 5, 2016|author=Eklund, Jonathan|work=[[Gaffa_(magazine)|Gaffa]]|access-date=September 14, 2018|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/6e43we/stream-yung-lean-associate-yung-bladees-chilly-gorgeous-debut-album-eversince|title=Stream Yung Lean Associate Bladee's Chilly, Gorgeous Debut Album 'Eversince'|date=May 25, 2016|author=Jenkins, Craig|work=[[Noisey]]|access-date=September 10, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Reichwald teamed up with production group Working on Dying to release his second mixtape, named after the group.\n\n2018 saw the release of Reichwald's sophomore album, ''[[Red Light (Bladee album)|Red Light]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/05/11/bladee-album-red-light-stream||title=Listen to Bladee\u2019s new album Red Light|date=May 11, 2018|author=Darville, Jordan|work=[[The Fader]]|access-date=September 10, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn July of 2018, Reichwald and fellow [[Drain Gang]] member [[Ecco2K]] walked Alyx Studio's S/S 2019 menswear show in Paris, on invitation from [[Matthew Williams (fashion designer)|Matthew Williams]].<ref name=Alyx> [https://www.vogue.com/fashion-shows/spring-2019-menswear/alyx \"Alyx S/S 19 Menswear\"], ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', Retrieved  6 February 2020</ref>\n\nReichwald's third mixtape, ''[[Icedancer]]'', was released December 28, 2018. This album was executively produced by Australian collective Ripsquad featuring production from Whitearmor and PJ Beats.  <ref name=Ice>[https://genius.com/albums/Bladee/Icedancer \"Icedancer\"], [[Genius]]. Retrieved on 6 February 2020.</ref>\n\nIn April of 2020, Reichwald released ''[[EXETER (Bladee album)|EXETER]]''[[EXETER (Bladee album)|,]] a nine song mixtape he recorded whilst in Gotland with [[Gud (music producer)|Gud]]. It is the first Bladee project produced by Gud on the [[YEAR0001]] label. <ref name=EXETER>[https://year0001.com/label/cases/yr0105 \"EXETER\"], [[YEAR0001]]. Retrieved on 8, April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nReichwald's musical style is characterized by a heavy use of [[autotune]] and a fusion of elements of [[Trap music|trap]], [[alternative R&B]], and [[cloud rap]].<ref name=\"Red Light album review\" /> i-D described his style as \"leaning towards emotional rap with obscure lo-fi production\" though saying, as of 2018, he had \"evolved into some sort of auto-tuned dark angel\".<ref name=\"need to know\" />\n\nIn a 2019 interview, Reichwald acknowledged that he frequently experiments with his music, and does not like to confine what he does to a single genre.<ref name=Jack>Angell, Jack, [https://www.thefader.com/2019/09/17/bladee-interview-drain-gang-trash-island \"Being Bladee\"], ''[[The Fader]]'', Retrieved on 6 February 2020.</ref> In the same interview, he stated that his music is therapeutic for him, and that he often uses it to vent.\n\nIn an interview with Reichwald, Jack Angell, a music writer for [[The Fader]], described Reichwald's sound as \"frostbitten futurism\" and remarked that Reichwald's music evokes \"a wide spectrum of emotion\".<ref name=Jack/>\n\nHe has received widespread attention for his collaborations and live performances with [[Yung Lean]].<ref name=\"debut Decay\" />\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n* ''[[Eversince (Bladee album)|Eversince]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Red Light (Bladee album)|Red Light]]'' (2018)\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''Gluee'' (2014)\n*''Working on Dying'' (2017)\n*''Icedancer'' (2018)\n* ''[[EXETER (Bladee album)|Exeter]]'' (2020)\n\n===Extended plays===\n* ''Rip Bladee'' (2016)\n*''Plastic Surgery'' (2017)<ref>{{Citation|title=Plastic Surgery|date=2017-02-06|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4hnlDFnmzRYgaVmJYUe89h?si=WUyxx8rsQLO4lcg3enKwnA|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n* ''Sunset in Silver City'' (2018)\n* ''Exile'' (2018)\n* ''Vanilla Sky'' (2019)\n\n===Collaborative mixtapes===\n*''GTBSG Compilation'' (2013) <small>(with Thaiboy Digital, Ecco2k, Yung Lean, Whitearmor, Yung Sherman)</small>\n*''AvP'' (2016) <small>(with Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n*''D&G'' (2017) <small>(with Ecco2k, Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n*''Trash Island'' (2019) <small>(with Ecco2k, Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Oxygen\" (2012)\n* \"Carwash\" (2013)\n* \"I Will Make You Bleed\" (2013) <small>(featuring Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n* \"My Magic Is Strong\" (2013)\n* \"Bleach\" (2013) <small>(featuring Ecco2k)</small>\n* \"Unreal\" (2014)\n* \"Dragonfly\" (2014)\n* \"Into Dust\" (2014)\n* \"Reborn\" (2014)\n* \"Psycho\" (2015) <small>(with Adamn Killa)</small>\n* \"Butterfly\" (2015) <small>(with Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n* \"Who Goes There\" (2016)\n* \"Who's Going To Find Me Tonight\" (2016)\n* \"Destroy Me\" (2017)\n* \"Gotham City\" (2017) <small>(with [[Yung Lean]])</small>\n* \"I Want It All\" (2017) <small>(with Cartier'GOD)</small>\n* \"Plastic Surgery\" (2017)\n* \"Wallet Won't Fold\" (2017)\n* \"Frosty the Snowman\" (2017)\n* \"Decay\" (2018)\n* \"I Chose to Be This Way\" (2018) <small>(with 16yrold)</small>\n* \"Red Velvet\" (2019) <small>(with [[Yung Lean]])</small>\n* \"Trash Star\" (2019)\n* \"All I Want\" (2019) <small>(with Mechatok)</small>\n* \"Apple\" (2019)\n* \"Girls Just Want To Have Fun\" (2020) <small>(with Ecco2k)</small>\n* \"Undergone\" (2020) <small>(with ssaliva)</small>\n\n===Guest appearances===\n* [[Yung Lean]] - \"Nitevision\" (2013)\n* Yung Lean - \"Heal You // Bladerunner\" (2013)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Gtblessgo\" (2014)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Don't Dance\" (2015)\n* Yung Lean - \"Highway Patrol\" (2016)\n* Yung Lean - \"Hocus Pocus\" (2016)\n* Yung Lean - \"Pearl Fountain\" (2016) <small>(featuring Black Kray)</small>\n* Yung Lean - \"Hennessy & Sailor Moon\" (2016)<ref name=\"HSSWeb\">{{cite web |last1=Renshaw |first1=David |title=Yung Lean Shares Surprise New Song, \"Hennessy & Sailor Moon\" |url=https://www.thefader.com/2016/11/25/yung-lean-hennessy--sailor-moon |website=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Yung Lean - \"Head 2 Toe\" (2016)\n*D33J - \"10K Froze\" (2018)\n* Yung Lean - \"Red Velvet\" (2019)\n*Varg - \"Perfect Violation\" (2019)\n* Chxpo - \"Do You Love Me\" (2019)\n*Sickboyrari - \"Famous\" (2019) <small>(featuring YSB OG and Yung Lean)</small>\n*Cartier'GOD - \"#LetMeGo\" (2019)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Bentley\" (2019)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Legendary Member\" (2019)\n*Sickboyrari - \"Blue\" (2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* {{Discogs artist|Bladee}}\n* {{Official website|http://year0001.com/|YEAR0001 Official}}\n\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Stockholm]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Bladee\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = File:Bladee in Toronto, Canada 2016.jpg\n| caption          = Bladee performing in 2016\n| birth_name       = Benjamin Reichwald\n| alias            = Ken Burns (Sm\u00f6g Boys)\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1994|4|9|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Stockholm, Sweden]]\n| genre            = [[cloud rap]], [[emo rap]], [[experimental pop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapper]], [[Singing|singer]], [[Fashion designer]], [[Graphic designer]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]], [[Digital Audio Workstation]], [[pitch-correction software]]\n| years_active     = 2008; 2011; 2012\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|[[YEAR0001]]|[[AWAL]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[Yung Lean]]|[[Thaiboy Digital]]|[[ECCO2K]]|Whitearmor|Yung Sherman|Gud|Adamn Killa|Cartier'GOD|Black Kray}}\n}}\n'''Benjamin Thage Dag Reichwald'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/artists/Bladee|title=Bladee|last=|first=|date=|website=Genius|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Borelli-Persson |first1=Laird |title=Is There Anything He Can't Do? Meet Stockholm's Stylish Multi-Hyphenate Zak Arogundade |url=https://www.vogue.com/article/musicians-zak-arogundade |website=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |publisher=Cond\u00e9 Nast |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref> (born 9 April 1994<ref>{{cite tweet |user=BladeeCity |number=718871748674850816 |date=9 Apr 2016 |title=Thanks everyone that wished me happy birthday}}</ref>), known professionally as '''Bladee''' (pronounced either \"blade\" or \"blade-e\"),<ref>\"Nardwuar vs. Yung Lean\", Youtube video, 12:36, posted by \"[[Nardwuar the Human Serviette|NardwuarServiette]]\", July 23, 2014, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=723ywF5faV4.</ref> is a Swedish rapper, singer, songwriter, record-producer, fashion designer and member of the musical group [[Drain Gang]].<ref name=Darville2018>{{cite web |last1=Darville |first1=Jordan |title=Listen to Bladee's new album Red Light |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/05/11/bladee-album-red-light-stream |website=[[The Fader]] |publisher=Andy Cohn |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"Red Light album review\">\"Bladee - Red Light ALBUM REVIEW\", Youtube video, 5:21, posted by \"[[Anthony Fantano|theneedledrop]]\", June 21, 2018, https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=FJwmTnjDkrI.</ref><ref name=\"debut Decay\">{{cite web |last1=Wang |first1=Steffanee |title=Bladee debuts \"Decay,\" our first taste of new album Red Light |url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/05/02/bladee-decay-video-red-light-album |website=[[The Fader]] |publisher=Andy Cohn |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref> \n\nHe released his debut album ''[[Eversince (Bladee album)|Eversince]]'' in 2016, and his second album ''[[Red Light (Bladee album)|Red Light]]'' in 2018\u2014both through Stockholm record label [[YEAR0001]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jenkins |first1=Craig |title=Stream Yung Lean Associate Bladee's Chilly, Gorgeous Debut Album 'Eversince' |url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/6e43we/stream-yung-lean-associate-yung-bladees-chilly-gorgeous-debut-album-eversince |website=[[Noisey]] |publisher=[[Vice Media]] |accessdate=7 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=Darville2018 /><ref>YEAR0001. Accessed July 19, 2018. http://www.year0001.com/.</ref> In addition to his music, Reichwald creates visual art, which frequently appears as cover art for his releases.<ref>Sami Baha. \"Bladee - Cover Up (Prod. Sami Baha)\". Soundcloud audio, 2:38, June 27, 2018. https://soundcloud.com/samibaha/bladee-cover-up-prod-sami-baha.</ref><ref>Bala Club. \"Woesum - Sapphire\". Soundcloud audio, 5:05, December 23, 2017. https://soundcloud.com/balaclub/woesum-sapphire.</ref> Reichwald also serves as the creative director for [[Yung Lean|Yung Lean's]] clothing line Sadboys Gear.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tesema |first1=Feleg |title=5 of Our Favorite New Collections & Where to Buy Them |url=https://www.highsnobiety.com/p/new-clothing-collections/ |website=[[Highsnobiety]] |publisher=Titel Media |accessdate=19 July 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"need to know\">{{cite web |last1=Dunn |first1=Frankie |title=10 things you need to know about bladee |url=https://i-d.vice.com/en_uk/article/xwmzgz/10-things-you-need-to-know-about-bladee |website=[[i-D]] |publisher=[[Vice Media|Vice]] |accessdate=24 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nBenjamin Reichwald was born 9 April 1994 in Stockholm, Sweden<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/BladeeCity/status/718871748674850816|title=Thanks everyone that wish me happy birthday|last=BLAD\u018eE|date=2016-04-09|website=@BladeeCity|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> and was raised mainly in the [[Skanstull]] area.<ref name=BeingBlade>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/09/17/bladee-interview-drain-gang-trash-island|title=Being Bladee|last=|first=|date=17 September 2019|website=The Fader|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> It was here where, in 2004, he met fellow Gravity Boys member Zak Arogundade, also known as Ecco2k. The two were classmates and formed a band titled \"Krossad\" when Reichwald was 13, which led to Reichwald's interest in music.<ref name=BeingBlade /> \n\nAfter leaving school, Reichwald began to get into making music whilst working at a daycare centre.<ref name=\"punk mix\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aqnb.com/2014/07/09/bladee-old-swedish-hardcore-punk-mix/|title=Bladee, old swedish hardcore punk mix|date=2014-07-09|website=atractivoquenobello|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nReichwald released a few tracks in 2011 under the name Ken Burns<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/Bladee-tony-hawk-lyrics|title=Tony Hawk|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ipMrg0edjBM|title=Tony Hawk|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>, but properly began releasing music in 2012. He eventually became friends with fellow Swedish rapper [[Yung Lean]], who was a friend of Reichwald's brother. Reichwald eventually sent a message to Sad Boys member Yung Sherman on SoundCloud, asking to collaborate, which resulted in a working relationship between his own Gravity Boys collective and Lean's Sad Boys Entertainment. Reichwald and Lean then made \"Heal You // Bladerunner\" from Lean's Unknown Death 2002 mixtape, which gave him attention from Lean's fanbase.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thefader.com/2014/07/16/taking-arizona-iced-tea-and-making-it-cry-an-interview-with-yung-lean-and-the-sad-boys|title=\"Taking Arizona Iced Tea and Making It Cry\": An Interview with Yung Lean and the Sad Boys|website=The FADER|language=en|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nReichwald released his debut-mixtape, ''GLUEE'' in 2014 on the YEAR0001 label<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://year0001.com/label/cases/yr0005|title=Bladee - Gluee {{!}} YEAR0001|website=year0001.com|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref> which was described as the \"summertime anthem for a suburban generation stuck scrolling through Twitter\".<ref name=\"punk mix\"\" /> The mixtape was successful on the audio distribution platform SoundCloud, racking up over 2 million plays.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=0nC0I-z9ONs|title=Always High|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> This mixtape, coupled with several singles going viral and features on Yung Leans debut mixtape [[Unknown Death 2002]] was able to rocket Bladee into underground hip hop fame.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://medium.com/thoughtsofamusicwriter/chronicling-how-sad-boys-and-shield-gang-became-swedens-top-rap-groups-c90925789e6c|title=Chronicling How Sad Boys and Shield Gang Became Sweden's Top Rap Groups|last=Osman|first=Jibril|date=2017-12-20|website=Medium|access-date=2019-04-14}}</ref>\n\nReichwald released his debut album, ''[[Eversince]]'' on May 25th, 2016.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thefader.com/2016/05/25/bladee-eversince-album-stream||title=Hear Swedish Sing-Rapper Bladee\u2019s Debut Album Eversince|date=May 25, 2016|author=Cooper, Duncan|work=[[The Fader]]|access-date=September 10, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref> The album received mixed reviews from mainstream outlets, but was well-received by underground and experimental critics.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://gaffa.se/recension/107456/kliver-ur-yung-leans-skugga-med-briljant-debut/||title=Kliver ur Yung Leans skugga med briljant debut|date=June 5, 2016|author=Eklund, Jonathan|work=[[Gaffa_(magazine)|Gaffa]]|access-date=September 14, 2018|language=sv}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://noisey.vice.com/en_us/article/6e43we/stream-yung-lean-associate-yung-bladees-chilly-gorgeous-debut-album-eversince|title=Stream Yung Lean Associate Bladee's Chilly, Gorgeous Debut Album 'Eversince'|date=May 25, 2016|author=Jenkins, Craig|work=[[Noisey]]|access-date=September 10, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Reichwald teamed up with production group Working on Dying to release his second mixtape, named after the group.\n\n2018 saw the release of Reichwald's sophomore album, ''[[Red Light (Bladee album)|Red Light]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thefader.com/2018/05/11/bladee-album-red-light-stream||title=Listen to Bladee\u2019s new album Red Light|date=May 11, 2018|author=Darville, Jordan|work=[[The Fader]]|access-date=September 10, 2018|language=en-us}}</ref>\n\nIn July of 2018, Reichwald and fellow [[Drain Gang]] member [[Ecco2K]] walked Alyx Studio's S/S 2019 menswear show in Paris, on invitation from [[Matthew Williams (fashion designer)|Matthew Williams]].<ref name=Alyx> [https://www.vogue.com/fashion-shows/spring-2019-menswear/alyx \"Alyx S/S 19 Menswear\"], ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'', Retrieved  6 February 2020</ref>\n\nReichwald's third mixtape, ''[[Icedancer]]'', was released December 28, 2018. This album was executively produced by Australian collective Ripsquad featuring production from Whitearmor and PJ Beats.  <ref name=Ice>[https://genius.com/albums/Bladee/Icedancer \"Icedancer\"], [[Genius]]. Retrieved on 6 February 2020.</ref>\n\nIn April of 2020, Reichwald released ''[[EXETER (Bladee album)|EXETER]]''[[EXETER (Bladee album)|,]] a nine song mixtape he recorded whilst in Gotland with [[Gud (music producer)|Gud]]. It is the first Bladee project produced by Gud on the [[YEAR0001]] label. <ref name=EXETER>[https://year0001.com/label/cases/yr0105 \"EXETER\"], [[YEAR0001]]. Retrieved on 8, April 2020.</ref>\n\n== Musical style ==\nReichwald's musical style is characterized by a heavy use of [[autotune]] and a fusion of elements of [[Trap music|trap]], [[alternative R&B]], and [[cloud rap]].<ref name=\"Red Light album review\" /> i-D described his style as \"leaning towards emotional rap with obscure lo-fi production\" though saying, as of 2018, he had \"evolved into some sort of auto-tuned dark angel\".<ref name=\"need to know\" />\n\nIn a 2019 interview, Reichwald acknowledged that he frequently experiments with his music, and does not like to confine what he does to a single genre.<ref name=Jack>Angell, Jack, [https://www.thefader.com/2019/09/17/bladee-interview-drain-gang-trash-island \"Being Bladee\"], ''[[The Fader]]'', Retrieved on 6 February 2020.</ref> In the same interview, he stated that his music is therapeutic for him, and that he often uses it to vent.\n\nIn an interview with Reichwald, Jack Angell, a music writer for [[The Fader]], described Reichwald's sound as \"frostbitten futurism\" and remarked that Reichwald's music evokes \"a wide spectrum of emotion\".<ref name=Jack/>\n\nHe has received widespread attention for his collaborations and live performances with [[Yung Lean]].<ref name=\"debut Decay\" />\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n\n* ''[[Eversince (Bladee album)|Eversince]]'' (2016)\n* ''[[Red Light (Bladee album)|Red Light]]'' (2018)\n\n===Mixtapes===\n* ''Gluee'' (2014)\n*''Working on Dying'' (2017)\n*''Icedancer'' (2018)\n* ''[[EXETER (Bladee album)|Exeter]]'' (2020)\n\n===Extended plays===\n* ''Rip Bladee'' (2016)\n*''Plastic Surgery'' (2017)<ref>{{Citation|title=Plastic Surgery|date=2017-02-06|url=https://open.spotify.com/album/4hnlDFnmzRYgaVmJYUe89h?si=WUyxx8rsQLO4lcg3enKwnA|language=en|access-date=2018-10-23}}</ref>\n* ''Sunset in Silver City'' (2018)\n* ''Exile'' (2018)\n* ''Vanilla Sky'' (2019)\n\n===Collaborative mixtapes===\n*''GTBSG Compilation'' (2013) <small>(with Thaiboy Digital, Ecco2k, Yung Lean, Whitearmor, Yung Sherman)</small>\n*''AvP'' (2016) <small>(with Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n*''D&G'' (2017) <small>(with Ecco2k, Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n*''Trash Island'' (2019) <small>(with Ecco2k, Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n\n===Singles===\n* \"Oxygen\" (2012)\n* \"Carwash\" (2013)\n* \"I Will Make You Bleed\" (2013) <small>(featuring Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n* \"My Magic Is Strong\" (2013)\n* \"Bleach\" (2013) <small>(featuring Ecco2k)</small>\n* \"Unreal\" (2014)\n* \"Dragonfly\" (2014)\n* \"Into Dust\" (2014)\n* \"Reborn\" (2014)\n* \"Psycho\" (2015) <small>(with Adamn Killa)</small>\n* \"Butterfly\" (2015) <small>(with Thaiboy Digital)</small>\n* \"Who Goes There\" (2016)\n* \"Who's Going To Find Me Tonight\" (2016)\n* \"Destroy Me\" (2017)\n* \"Gotham City\" (2017) <small>(with [[Yung Lean]])</small>\n* \"I Want It All\" (2017) <small>(with Cartier'GOD)</small>\n* \"Plastic Surgery\" (2017)\n* \"Wallet Won't Fold\" (2017)\n* \"Frosty the Snowman\" (2017)\n* \"Decay\" (2018)\n* \"I Chose to Be This Way\" (2018) <small>(with 16yrold)</small>\n* \"Red Velvet\" (2019) <small>(with [[Yung Lean]])</small>\n* \"Trash Star\" (2019)\n* \"All I Want\" (2019) <small>(with Mechatok)</small>\n* \"Apple\" (2019)\n* \"Girls Just Want To Have Fun\" (2020) <small>(with Ecco2k)</small>\n* \"Undergone\" (2020) <small>(with ssaliva)</small>\n\n===Guest appearances===\n* [[Yung Lean]] - \"Nitevision\" (2013)\n* Yung Lean - \"Heal You // Bladerunner\" (2013)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Gtblessgo\" (2014)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Don't Dance\" (2015)\n* Yung Lean - \"Highway Patrol\" (2016)\n* Yung Lean - \"Hocus Pocus\" (2016)\n* Yung Lean - \"Pearl Fountain\" (2016) <small>(featuring Black Kray)</small>\n* Yung Lean - \"Hennessy & Sailor Moon\" (2016)<ref name=\"HSSWeb\">{{cite web |last1=Renshaw |first1=David |title=Yung Lean Shares Surprise New Song, \"Hennessy & Sailor Moon\" |url=https://www.thefader.com/2016/11/25/yung-lean-hennessy--sailor-moon |website=[[The Fader]] |accessdate=23 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Yung Lean - \"Head 2 Toe\" (2016)\n*D33J - \"10K Froze\" (2018)\n* Yung Lean - \"Red Velvet\" (2019)\n* Varg - \"Perfect Violation\" (2018)\n* Chxpo - \"Do You Love Me\" (2019)\n*Sickboyrari - \"Famous\" (2019) <small>(featuring YSB OG and Yung Lean)</small>\n*Cartier'GOD - \"#LetMeGo\" (2019)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Bentley\" (2019)\n* Thaiboy Digital - \"Legendary Member\" (2019)\n*Sickboyrari - \"Blue\" (2019)\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External Links==\n* {{Discogs artist|Bladee}}\n* {{Official website|http://year0001.com/|YEAR0001 Official}}\n\n[[Category:1994 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Swedish rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Stockholm]]\n", "name_user": "Cantabile22", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGuest appearances", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bladee"}
{"title_page": "Flugpost am Rhein und am Main", "text_new": "[[File:Rhine and Main June 1912 airmail flight postcard.jpg|thumb|upright=1.24|Postcard flown on 18 June 1912 on Frankfurt am Rhein to Mainz airmail service]]\n\nThe '''Flugpost am Rhein und am Main''' (English: Airmail on the [[Rhine]] and [[Main (river)|Main]]) of 1912 was an early landmark in [[postal history]], in which mail flights took place between [[Frankfurt am Main]] [[Mainz]], [[Offenbach am Main]], [[Worms, Germany|Worms]] and [[Darmstadt]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gibson |first=Gary |title=Duchess von Hessen and the Flight of the ''Gelber Hund'' |journal=Scribblings |volume=20 |issue=5 |pages=1-5 |publisher=Rocky Mountain Philatelic Library |location=Denver |date=September 2012 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503035630/http://www.rmpldenver.com/pdf_files/2012sepoctscribblings.pdf |OCLC=61313704 |accessdate=2019-12-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503035630/http://www.rmpldenver.com/pdf_files/2012sepoctscribblings.pdf |archivedate=2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Event overview ==\n[[File:DBPB_1962_230_Luftpostbef\u00f6rderung.jpg|alt=|thumb|On the occasion of \"50 years of airmail transport\" a stamp was made in [[Berlin]] in 1962 showing a four-jet airplane. In front of the plane was the \"Yellow Dog\" from 1912 from the Euler company.]]\nThe [[airmail]] on the Rhine and Main took place from 9\u201323 June 1912 under the patronage of Grand Duke [[Ernst Ludwig]] and Grand Duchess [[Eleonore of Hesse-Rheinfels-Rotenburg|Eleonore of Hesse]]. The proceeds went to the ''Gro\u00dfherzogliche Zentrale f\u00fcr Mutter- und S\u00e4uglingsf\u00fcrsorge in Hessen'' (Grand Ducal Head Office for Mother and Infant Welfare in Hesse). The airmail was carried by the [[airship]] ''Schwaben'' and August Euler's aircraft ''Gelber Hund''. In order for the cards to be transported they had to be provided with semi-official [[Postage stamp|stamp]]s, called [[airmail stamps]]s. Although these had no postal value, but were instead issued by the event organizer, they received a postal validation.\n\n== First flight ==\nOn 10 June 1912 at 19:04 hours, [[Ferdinand von Hiddessen]] flew from Frankfurt-[[Niederrad]] with 40 kilograms of mail to Darmstadt in a biplane of the brand Euler, named \"Gelber Hund\" because of its yellow wings. He covered the 27-kilometer distance in 13:27 minutes. A mail exchange took place in Darmstadt and then Hiddessen flew to [[Worms, Germany|Worms]] with 79 kg of mail, where he landed at about 9 pm. This flight with the Yellow Dog, owing to its notoriety in postal history, marked the beginning of the airmail week \u2014 from June 10 to June 23, 1912 on the Rhine and [[Main (river)|Main]] rivers, taking place in Worms, Darmstadt, Frankfurt am Main, Mainz and Offenbach. It is regarded as one of the first major airmail events with official airmail transport in the world and thus marks the beginning of German airmail history. A flight postcard was produced for the postal transport, which had to be franked with an airmail stamp in addition to the regular postcard postage of 5 [[Pfennig]]s.\n\n== Literature ==\n* Das Archiv, Hrsg. [[:de:Deutsche_Gesellschaft_f\u00fcr_Post-_und_Telekommunikationsgeschichte|Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Post- und Telekommunikationsgeschichte]]; ISSN [https://zdb-katalog.de/list.xhtml?t=iss%3D%220947-9945%22&key=cql 0947-9945]:\n** O. K\u00fchndelt: ''Vor 50 Jahren: Erste Postluftfahrt''; (Archiv f\u00fcr Deutsche Postgeschichte); Booklet 1 from 1962; S. 3\u201312\n** Imke Schabel: ''Der Weltweit erste Postflug \u2013 Von Frankfurt \u00fcber Darmstadt nach Worms''; Booklet 1/2 from 2002; S. 120\u2013121\n** Tanja Neumann: ''Eine Idee lernt fliegen \u2013 Die Initiative Luftfahrtmuseum August Euler''; Booklet 2 from 2012; S. 40\u201341\n* Ausstellungskatalog: 100 Jahre Flugpost an Rhein und Main; 11. June 2012\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.flugpost-rhein-main.de/ Flugpost am Rhein und am Main]\n\n[[Category:Frankfurt]]\n[[Category:Postal history of Germany]]\n[[Category:Airmail]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Rhine and Main June 1912 airmail flight postcard.jpg|thumb|upright=1.24|Postcard flown on 18 June 1912 on Frankfurt am Rhein to Mainz airmail service]]\n\nThe '''Flugpost am Rhein und am Main''' (English: Airmail on the [[Rhine]] and [[Main (river)|Main]]) of 1912 was an early landmark in [[postal history]], in which mail flights took place between [[Frankfurt am Main]] [[Mainz]], [[Offenbach am Main]], [[Worms, Germany|Worms]] and [[Darmstadt]].<ref>{{Cite journal |last=Gibson |first=Gary |title=Duchess von Hessen and the Flight of the ''Gelber Hund'' |journal=Scribblings |volume=20 |issue=5 |pages=1-5 |publisher=Rocky Mountain Philatelic Library |location=Denver |date=September 2012 |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503035630/http://www.rmpldenver.com/pdf_files/2012sepoctscribblings.pdf |OCLC=61313704 |accessdate=2019-12-08 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503035630/http://www.rmpldenver.com/pdf_files/2012sepoctscribblings.pdf |archivedate=2015-11-14}}</ref>\n\n== Event overview ==\n[[File:DBPB_1962_230_Luftpostbef\u00f6rderung.jpg|alt=|thumb|On the occasion of \"50 years of airmail transport\" a stamp was made in [[Berlin]] in 1962 showing a four-jet airplane. In front of the plane was the \"Yellow Dog\" from 1912 from the Euler company.]]\nThe [[airmail]] on the Rhine and Main took place from 9\u201323 June 1912 under the patronage of Grand Duke [[Ernst Ludwig]] and Grand Duchess [[Eleonore of Hesse-Rheinfels-Rotenburg|Eleonore of Hesse]]. The proceeds went to the ''Gro\u00dfherzogliche Zentrale f\u00fcr Mutter- und S\u00e4uglingsf\u00fcrsorge in Hessen'' (Grand Ducal Head Office for Mother and Infant Welfare in Hesse). The airmail was carried by the [[airship]] ''Schwaben'' and August Euler's aircraft ''Gelber Hund''. In order for the cards to be transported they had to be provided with semi-official [[stamp]]s, called [[airmail stamps]]s. Although these had no postal value, but were instead issued by the event organizer, they received a postal validation.\n\n== First flight ==\nOn 10 June 1912 at 19:04 hours, [[Ferdinand von Hiddessen]] flew from Frankfurt-[[Niederrad]] with 40 kilograms of mail to Darmstadt in a biplane of the brand Euler, named \"Gelber Hund\" because of its yellow wings. He covered the 27-kilometer distance in 13:27 minutes. A mail exchange took place in Darmstadt and then Hiddessen flew to [[Worms, Germany|Worms]] with 79 kg of mail, where he landed at about 9 pm. This flight with the Yellow Dog, owing to its notoriety in postal history, marked the beginning of the airmail week \u2014 from June 10 to June 23, 1912 on the Rhine and [[Main (river)|Main]] rivers, taking place in Worms, Darmstadt, Frankfurt am Main, Mainz and Offenbach. It is regarded as one of the first major airmail events with official airmail transport in the world and thus marks the beginning of German airmail history. A flight postcard was produced for the postal transport, which had to be franked with an airmail stamp in addition to the regular postcard postage of 5 [[Pfennig]]s.\n\n== Literature ==\n* Das Archiv, Hrsg. [[:de:Deutsche_Gesellschaft_f\u00fcr_Post-_und_Telekommunikationsgeschichte|Deutsche Gesellschaft f\u00fcr Post- und Telekommunikationsgeschichte]]; ISSN [https://zdb-katalog.de/list.xhtml?t=iss%3D%220947-9945%22&key=cql 0947-9945]:\n** O. K\u00fchndelt: ''Vor 50 Jahren: Erste Postluftfahrt''; (Archiv f\u00fcr Deutsche Postgeschichte); Booklet 1 from 1962; S. 3\u201312\n** Imke Schabel: ''Der Weltweit erste Postflug \u2013 Von Frankfurt \u00fcber Darmstadt nach Worms''; Booklet 1/2 from 2002; S. 120\u2013121\n** Tanja Neumann: ''Eine Idee lernt fliegen \u2013 Die Initiative Luftfahrtmuseum August Euler''; Booklet 2 from 2012; S. 40\u201341\n* Ausstellungskatalog: 100 Jahre Flugpost an Rhein und Main; 11. June 2012\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.flugpost-rhein-main.de/ Flugpost am Rhein und am Main]\n\n[[Category:Frankfurt]]\n[[Category:Postal history of Germany]]\n[[Category:Airmail]]\n", "name_user": "BD2412", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEvent overview:Fixing links to disambiguation pages, improving links, other minor cleanup tasks", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Flugpost_am_Rhein_und_am_Main"}
{"title_page": "DigiCert", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = DigiCert Inc.\n| logo = DigiCert-Logo.svg\n| type = [[Private company]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|2003}}\n| location_city = [[Lehi, Utah]], U.S.\n| num_locations = 12\n| num_employees = 1,000+\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = CEO: John Merrill, CIO: Jason Sabin, CTO: Dan Timpson\n| industry = [[Internet security]], [[Public key infrastructure]], [[IoT security]]\n| homepage = {{URL|www.digicert.com/}}\n}}{{Lead extra info|date=August 2019}}{{Lead rewrite|date=August 2019}}'''DigiCert, Inc.''' is a US-based [[technology company]] focused on [[digital security]] and headquartered in [[Lehi, Utah]] with international offices in Australia, Ireland, Japan, India, South Africa, Switzerland and United Kingdom. As a [[certificate authority]] (CA) and [[trusted third party]], DigiCert provides the [[public key infrastructure]] (PKI) and validation required for issuing [[Public key certificate|digital certificates]] or [[Transport Layer Security|TLS/SSL]] certificates. These certificates are used to verify and authenticate the identities of organizations and domains and to protect the privacy and data integrity of users\u2019 digital interactions with [[web browser]]s, email clients, documents, software programs, apps, networks and connected [[Internet of things|IoT]] devices.\n\nThe company's products and services also include private and managed PKI deployments, the DigiCert CertCentral certificate management platform, the DigiCert PKI Platform and full customer support.\n\nIn 2019, the company announced a new [[Research and development|R&D]] division called DigiCert Labs, \"... an initiative dedicated to researching and developing innovative approaches to security challenges.\"<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/digicert-labs-to-innovate-new-security-technologies-that-address-emerging-threats-through-collaboration-with-academic-and-industry-research-300787847.html \u201cDigiCert Labs to innovate new security technologies that address emerging threats through collaboration with academic and industry research\u201d]. ''[[PR Newswire]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref> DigiCert Labs will collaborate with other enterprise labs \u2013 including [[Microsoft Research]], Utimaco, ISARA and [[Gemalto]] \u2013 and make grants to universities for the study of topics related to [[authentication]], [[data integrity]], [[encryption]] and [[Identity management|identity]]. Initial research projects will focus on [[post-quantum cryptography]] and [[machine learning]].<ref>Barker, Sara. [https://securitybrief.eu/story/digicert-labs-to-research-postquantum-cryptography-ml \u201cDigiCert Labs to research postquantum cryptography and ML\u201d]. ''SecurityBrief EMEA.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref>\n\nDigiCert is a member of the [[CA/Browser Forum]], an industry consortium that creates guidelines and standards for participating certificate authorities and web browsers.<ref>[https://cabforum.org/members/ CA/Browser Forum Members]. ''[[CA/Browser Forum]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28</ref> Dean Coclin, Sr. Director of Business Development at DigiCert, will serve as Vice-Chairperson of the CA/Browser Forum from Nov. 1, 2018 until Oct. 31, 2020.<ref>[https://cabforum.org/leadership/ CA/Browser Forum Leadership]. ''[[CA/Browser Forum]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2015, in one of the largest investments in a Utah-based company to date, private equity firm [[Thoma Bravo]] acquired a majority stake in DigiCert, with [[TA Associates]] a leading global growth private equity firm, holding a minority share. Thoma Bravo was quoted as saying, \"DigiCert represents an outstanding investment opportunity to back a market leader\u2026 known for its consistent innovation and first-rate customer service.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eweek.com/security/thoma-bravo-invests-in-security-firm-digicert.html|title=Thoma Bravo Invests in Security Firm DigiCert|author=Sean Michael Kerner|date=2015-08-28|website=Eweek.com|accessdate=2015-12-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Clearlake Capital Group, L.P., a leading private investment firm, and TA Associates, an existing investor, reached an agreement to make a strategic growth investment in DigiCert. As part of the transaction, Clearlake and TA Associates become equal partners in the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ta.com/about/news/clearlake-capital-group-and-ta-associates-to-make-a-strategic-growth-investment-in-digicert|title=News {{!}} TA|website=TA Associates|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clearlake.com/clearlake-capital-group-and-ta-associates-to-make-a-strategic-growth-investment-in-digicert/|title=CLEARLAKE CAPITAL GROUP AND TA ASSOCIATES TO MAKE A STRATEGIC GROWTH INVESTMENT IN DIGICERT|date=2019-07-09|website=Clearlake Capital|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\nDigiCert Inc. is of no relation to Digicert Sdn. Bhd, a Malaysian-based certification authority that issues certificates with weak keys and had its trust revoked by web browsers.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.entrust.net/advisories/malaysia.htm |title=SSL Certificate Support - Entrust, Inc |website=Entrust.net |date= |accessdate=2015-12-25}}</ref><ref>[https://blog.mozilla.org/security/2011/11/03/revoking-trust-in-digicert-sdn-bhd-intermediate-certificate-authority/ Revoking Trust in DigiCert Sdn. Bhd Intermediate Certificate Authority], [[Mozilla]]. \"DigiCert Sdn. Bhd is a Malaysian subordinate CA under Entrust and Verizon (GTE CyberTrust). It bears no affiliation whatsoever with the US-based corporation DigiCert, Inc., which is a member of Mozilla's root program.\"</ref><ref>[https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/security/advisory/2641690 Microsoft Security Advisory (2641690)] \"DigiCert Sdn. Bhd is not affiliated with the corporation DigiCert, Inc., which is a member of the Microsoft Root Certificate Program.\"</ref>\n\n==History==\nDigiCert was founded by Ken Bretschneider in 2003. Bretschneider served as CEO and chairman of the board until 2012 when he was appointed Executive chairman and Nicholas Hales became CEO.<ref>[https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=53925270&itype=CMSID \u201cUtah\u2019s DigiCert reorganizes its management\u201d]. ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref> In 2016, the company named John Merrill CEO.<ref>[https://www.heraldextra.com/business/local/digicert-names-ceo-green-house-center-anniversary-utah-labor-market/article_ee0d820f-f132-5021-b261-8ef510fcf94d.html \u201cDigiCert names CEO\u201d]. [[Daily Herald (Utah)|''Daily Herald'']]''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, DigiCert acquired the CyberTrust Enterprise SSL business from [[Verizon Enterprise Solutions]], becoming the world's second-largest certificate authority for high-assurance or [[Extended Validation Certificate|extended validation]] (EV) TLS/SSL certificates.<ref>[https://www.digicert.com/news/2015-06-23-digicert-acquires-verizon-business/ \u201cDigiCert Acquires Verizon Enterprise SSL Business\u201d]. ''DigiCert.com.'' Retrieved 2019-03-01.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, DigiCert acquired the TLS/SSL and PKI businesses from the world's largest certificate authority, [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]] (including brands [[GeoTrust]], RapidSSL, [[Thawte]] and [[Verisign]]), for $950&nbsp;million.<ref>Raymond, Art. [https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865686081/Lehis-DigiCert-swallows-web-security-competitor-in-1-billion-deal.html \u201cLehi\u2019s DigiCert swallows web security competitor in $1 billion deal\u201d.] ''[[Deseret News]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-03-01.</ref> The acquisition resulted from questions first raised in 2015 by web browsers [[Google]] and [[Mozilla]] about the authenticity of certificates issued by Symantec, which represented one-third of all TLS/SSL certificates on the web.<ref>Sharwood, Simon. [https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/08/03/symantec_q1_2018 \u201cSymantec offloads its certs and web security biz to DigiCert\u201d]. ''[[The Register]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref><ref>Constantin, Lucian. [https://www.computerworld.com/article/3184573/to-punish-symantec-google-may-distrust-a-third-of-the-webs-ssl-certificates.html \u201cTo punish Symantec, Google may distrust a third of the web\u2019s SSL certificates\u201d]. ''[[Computerworld]].'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref> In Sep. 2017, Google and Mozilla announced they would \"... reduce, and ultimately remove, trust in Symantec's infrastructure in order to uphold users\u2019 security and privacy when browsing the web.\" The final distrust deadline for certificates chaining to Symantec roots was set for Oct. 2018.<ref>[https://security.googleblog.com/2017/09/chromes-plan-to-distrust-symantec.html \u201cChrome\u2019s Plan to Distrust Symantec Certificates\u201d]. ''[[Google]].'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref> Symantec agreed to transfer its certificate business to its top TLS/SSL competitor, DigiCert, whose roots were trusted by browsers.<ref>[https://www.eweek.com/security/digicert-closes-acquisition-of-symantec-s-website-ssl-security-unit \"DigiCert Closes Acquisition of Symantec's Website SSL Security Unit\"]. ''[[eWeek]].'' Retrieved 2019-03-11.</ref> In Dec. 2017, DigiCert began issuing free replacements for all distrusted certificates from Symantec, GeoTrust, RapidSSL, Thawte and VeriSign. By Oct. 2018, the company had revalidated more than 550,000 organizational identities and issued more than 5 million replacement certificates for affected customers.<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/digicert-works-with-its-customers-and-partners-to-successfully-move-past-googles-distrust-of-symantec-tls-certificates-300745385.html \u201cDigiCert works with its customers and partners to successfully move past Google\u2019s distrust of Symantec TLS certificates\u201d]. ''[[PR Newswire]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-03-01.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, DigiCert acquired QuoVadis, a trust service provider (TSP) headquartered in Switzerland offering [[qualified digital certificate]]s, PKI services and PrimoSign electronic signature software. Qualified digital certificates from QuoVadis (now backed by DigiCert) comply with [[eIDAS]], a set of [[European Union|EU]] standards for electronic transactions requiring legal proof of authentication. The EU [[Payment Services Directive]] mandates that banks and other financial institutions operating in Europe begin using qualified digital certificates by Jun. 2019. According to DigiCert, \"... the QuoVadis acquisition aligns with the company's vision of providing globally dispersed and robust PKI-based solutions with local support.\"<ref>Barker, Sara. [https://securitybrief.eu/story/digicert-s-quovadis-acquisition-extends-pki-expertise-in-eu \u201cDigiCert\u2019s QuoVadis acquisition extends PKI expertise in Europe\u201d]. ''SecurityBrief EMEA.'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|https://www.digicert.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Digicert}}\n[[Category:Certificate authorities]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Utah]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Utah]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Utah County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Lehi, Utah]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=September 2017}}\n\n{{Infobox company\n| name = DigiCert Inc.\n| logo = DigiCert-Logo.svg\n| type = [[Private company]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|2003}}\n| location_city = [[Lehi, Utah]], [[United States]]\n| num_locations = 12\n| num_employees = 1,000+\n| area_served = Worldwide\n| key_people = CEO: John Merrill, CIO: Jason Sabin, CTO: Dan Timpson\n| industry = [[Internet security]], [[Public key infrastructure]], [[IoT security]]\n| homepage = {{URL|https://www.digicert.com/}}\n}}{{Lead extra info|date=August 2019}}{{Lead rewrite|date=August 2019}}'''DigiCert, Inc.''' is a US-based [[technology company]] focused on [[digital security]] and headquartered in [[Lehi, Utah]] with international offices in [[Australia]], [[Ireland]], [[Japan]], [[India]], [[South Africa]], [[Switzerland]] and [[United Kingdom]]. As a [[certificate authority]] (CA) and [[trusted third party]], DigiCert provides the [[public key infrastructure]] (PKI) and validation required for issuing [[Public key certificate|digital certificates]] or [[Transport Layer Security|TLS/SSL]] certificates. These certificates are used to verify and authenticate the identities of organizations and domains and to protect the privacy and data integrity of users\u2019 digital interactions with [[Web browser|web browsers]], email clients, documents, software programs, apps, networks and connected [[Internet of things|IoT]] devices.\n\nThe company\u2019s products and services also include private and managed PKI deployments, the DigiCert CertCentral certificate management platform, the DigiCert PKI Platform and full customer support.\n\nIn 2019, the company announced a new [[Research and development|R&D]] division called DigiCert Labs, \u201c... an initiative dedicated to researching and developing innovative approaches to security challenges.\u201d<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/digicert-labs-to-innovate-new-security-technologies-that-address-emerging-threats-through-collaboration-with-academic-and-industry-research-300787847.html \u201cDigiCert Labs to innovate new security technologies that address emerging threats through collaboration with academic and industry research\u201d]. ''[[PR Newswire]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref> DigiCert Labs will collaborate with other enterprise labs \u2014 including [[Microsoft Research]], Utimaco, ISARA and [[Gemalto]] \u2014 and make grants to universities for the study of topics related to [[authentication]], [[data integrity]], [[encryption]] and [[Identity management|identity]]. Initial research projects will focus on [[post-quantum cryptography]] and [[machine learning]].<ref>Barker, Sara. [https://securitybrief.eu/story/digicert-labs-to-research-postquantum-cryptography-ml \u201cDigiCert Labs to research postquantum cryptography and ML\u201d]. ''SecurityBrief EMEA.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref>\n\nDigiCert is a member of the [[CA/Browser Forum]], an industry consortium that creates guidelines and standards for participating certificate authorities and web browsers.<ref>[https://cabforum.org/members/ CA/Browser Forum Members]. ''[[CA/Browser Forum]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28</ref> Dean Coclin, Sr. Director of Business Development at DigiCert, will serve as Vice-Chairperson of the CA/Browser Forum from Nov. 1, 2018 until Oct. 31, 2020.<ref>[https://cabforum.org/leadership/ CA/Browser Forum Leadership]. ''[[CA/Browser Forum]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2015, in one of the largest investments in a Utah-based company to date, private equity firm [[Thoma Bravo]] acquired a majority stake in DigiCert, with [[TA Associates]] a leading global growth private equity firm, holding a minority share. Thoma Bravo was quoted as saying, \u201cDigiCert represents an outstanding investment opportunity to back a market leader\u2026 known for its consistent innovation and first-rate customer service.\u201d <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eweek.com/security/thoma-bravo-invests-in-security-firm-digicert.html|title=Thoma Bravo Invests in Security Firm DigiCert|author=Sean Michael Kerner|date=2015-08-28|website=Eweek.com|accessdate=2015-12-25}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Clearlake Capital Group, L.P., a leading private investment firm, and TA Associates, an existing investor, reached an agreement to make a strategic growth investment in DigiCert. As part of the transaction, Clearlake and TA Associates become equal partners in the company.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ta.com/about/news/clearlake-capital-group-and-ta-associates-to-make-a-strategic-growth-investment-in-digicert|title=News {{!}} TA|website=TA Associates|language=en|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clearlake.com/clearlake-capital-group-and-ta-associates-to-make-a-strategic-growth-investment-in-digicert/|title=CLEARLAKE CAPITAL GROUP AND TA ASSOCIATES TO MAKE A STRATEGIC GROWTH INVESTMENT IN DIGICERT|date=2019-07-09|website=Clearlake Capital|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-16}}</ref>\n\nDigiCert Inc. is of no relation to Digicert Sdn. Bhd, a Malaysian-based certification authority that issues certificates with weak keys and had its trust revoked by web browsers.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.entrust.net/advisories/malaysia.htm |title=SSL Certificate Support - Entrust, Inc |website=Entrust.net |date= |accessdate=2015-12-25}}</ref><ref>[https://blog.mozilla.org/security/2011/11/03/revoking-trust-in-digicert-sdn-bhd-intermediate-certificate-authority/ Revoking Trust in DigiCert Sdn. Bhd Intermediate Certificate Authority], [[Mozilla]]. \"DigiCert Sdn. Bhd is a Malaysian subordinate CA under Entrust and Verizon (GTE CyberTrust). It bears no affiliation whatsoever with the US-based corporation DigiCert, Inc., which is a member of Mozilla\u2019s root program.\"</ref><ref>[https://technet.microsoft.com/en-us/security/advisory/2641690 Microsoft Security Advisory (2641690)] \"DigiCert Sdn. Bhd is not affiliated with the corporation DigiCert, Inc., which is a member of the Microsoft Root Certificate Program.\"</ref>\n\n==History==\nDigiCert was founded by Ken Bretschneider in 2003. Bretschneider served as CEO and Chairman of the Board until 2012 when he was appointed Executive Chairman and Nicholas Hales became CEO.<ref>[https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=53925270&itype=CMSID \u201cUtah\u2019s DigiCert reorganizes its management\u201d]. ''[[The Salt Lake Tribune]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref> In 2016, the company named John Merrill CEO.<ref>[https://www.heraldextra.com/business/local/digicert-names-ceo-green-house-center-anniversary-utah-labor-market/article_ee0d820f-f132-5021-b261-8ef510fcf94d.html \u201cDigiCert names CEO\u201d]. [[Daily Herald (Utah)|''Daily Herald'']]''.'' Retrieved 2019-02-28.</ref>\n\nIn 2015, DigiCert acquired the CyberTrust Enterprise SSL business from [[Verizon Enterprise Solutions]], becoming the world\u2019s second-largest certificate authority for high-assurance or [[Extended Validation Certificate|extended validation]] (EV) TLS/SSL certificates.<ref>[https://www.digicert.com/news/2015-06-23-digicert-acquires-verizon-business/ \u201cDigiCert Acquires Verizon Enterprise SSL Business\u201d]. ''DigiCert.com.'' Retrieved 2019-03-01.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, DigiCert acquired the TLS/SSL and PKI businesses from the world\u2019s largest certificate authority, [[NortonLifeLock|Symantec]] (including brands [[GeoTrust]], RapidSSL, [[Thawte]] and [[Verisign|VeriSign]]), for $950 million.<ref>Raymond, Art. [https://www.deseretnews.com/article/865686081/Lehis-DigiCert-swallows-web-security-competitor-in-1-billion-deal.html \u201cLehi\u2019s DigiCert swallows web security competitor in $1 billion deal\u201d.] ''[[Deseret News]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-03-01.</ref> The acquisition resulted from questions first raised in 2015 by web browsers [[Google]] and [[Mozilla]] about the authenticity of certificates issued by Symantec, which represented one-third of all TLS/SSL certificates on the web.<ref>Sharwood, Simon. [https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/08/03/symantec_q1_2018 \u201cSymantec offloads its certs and web security biz to DigiCert\u201d]. ''[[The Register]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref><ref>Constantin, Lucian. [https://www.computerworld.com/article/3184573/to-punish-symantec-google-may-distrust-a-third-of-the-webs-ssl-certificates.html \u201cTo punish Symantec, Google may distrust a third of the web\u2019s SSL certificates\u201d]. ''[[Computerworld]].'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref> In Sep. 2017, Google and Mozilla announced they would \u201c... reduce, and ultimately remove, trust in Symantec\u2019s infrastructure in order to uphold users\u2019 security and privacy when browsing the web.\u201d The final distrust deadline for certificates chaining to Symantec roots was set for Oct. 2018.<ref>[https://security.googleblog.com/2017/09/chromes-plan-to-distrust-symantec.html \u201cChrome\u2019s Plan to Distrust Symantec Certificates\u201d]. ''[[Google]].'' Retrieved 2019-03-05.</ref> Symantec agreed to transfer its certificate business to its top TLS/SSL competitor, DigiCert, whose roots were trusted by browsers.<ref>[https://www.eweek.com/security/digicert-closes-acquisition-of-symantec-s-website-ssl-security-unit \"DigiCert Closes Acquisition of Symantec's Website SSL Security Unit\"]. ''[[eWeek]].'' Retrieved 2019-03-11.</ref> In Dec. 2017, DigiCert began issuing free replacements for all distrusted certificates from Symantec, GeoTrust, RapidSSL, Thawte and VeriSign. By Oct. 2018, the company had revalidated more than 550,000 organizational identities and issued more than 5 million replacement certificates for affected customers.<ref>[https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/digicert-works-with-its-customers-and-partners-to-successfully-move-past-googles-distrust-of-symantec-tls-certificates-300745385.html \u201cDigiCert works with its customers and partners to successfully move past Google\u2019s distrust of Symantec TLS certificates\u201d]. ''[[PR Newswire]]''''.'' Retrieved 2019-03-01.</ref>\n\nIn 2018, DigiCert acquired QuoVadis, a trust service provider (TSP) headquartered in Switzerland offering [[Qualified digital certificate|qualified digital certificates]], PKI services and PrimoSign electronic signature software. Qualified digital certificates from QuoVadis (now backed by DigiCert) comply with [[eIDAS]], a set of [[European Union|EU]] standards for electronic transactions requiring legal proof of authentication. The EU [[Payment Services Directive]] mandates that banks and other financial institutions operating in Europe begin using qualified digital certificates by Jun. 2019. According to DigiCert, \u201c... the QuoVadis acquisition aligns with the company\u2019s vision of providing globally dispersed and robust PKI-based solutions with local support.\u201d<ref>Barker, Sara. [https://securitybrief.eu/story/digicert-s-quovadis-acquisition-extends-pki-expertise-in-eu \u201cDigiCert\u2019s QuoVadis acquisition extends PKI expertise in Europe\u201d]. ''SecurityBrief EMEA.'' Retrieved 2019-03-05. </ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official|https://www.digicert.com/}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Digicert}}\n[[Category:Certificate authorities]]\n[[Category:Privately held companies based in Utah]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2003]]\n[[Category:2003 establishments in Utah]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Utah County, Utah]]\n[[Category:Lehi, Utah]]\n", "name_user": "Walter G\u00f6rlitz", "label": "safe", "comment": "perWP:OVERLINK,MOS:ACRO, Generalformattingbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DigiCert"}
